Here‚Äôs the full story: two underground German wasp nest behind my retaining wall in the backyard were discovered this summer and today, a 3rd massive colony nest hanging under the tree was found in the front of my yard. Used an inspection camera to poke thru the wall gap to see what was happening inside, and a night vision camera to check on the overhanging one without spooking them with light. Videos and photos are in sequential order showing the eradication of all three colonies.

üíõüíï Yellow Lady Loves To Bite in Pink Petal üíõüíï Look who is so dashing on the red carpet? Ohh lala beautiful wasp lady! Until this day I'm not quite sure what she was doing... crawling through every single petal of a bright pink dahlia. She kept popping up and disappearing again in pinkishness. Wobbling and buzzing.

Tip üíï: Take shots from different angles. So often I have an idea in mind, of what the final result should be... but in the field it plays out differently. A bug rarely does what you 'want' - as it should :D - and before you know it, it has more important stuff to do than model for you. When I get home and review the pics, I can be surprised how an angle I wasn't going for in the first place, actually turned out to be one of the best shots...

Off to the vets with Gem this morning, she has developed an allergy to something.  I suspect seafood but too soon to tell.  We got some very expensive tablets (non steroid) to try and break the itchy cycle.  After being prodded, probed üò± and scrapped, she was rewarded with a walk by the beach.  When we got home and I went to let her out of the truck, she thanked me by representing her breakfast on the backseat.  Thank goodness I‚Äôd invested in canvas covers!

Do you have problems with Wasps around the home?

Hawkeye Wasp Lure is recommended if you only have a couple of wasps around your property.

Hawkeye Wasp Bait is recommended if you have a more invasive wasp infestation as this product will wipe out the whole nest.

Both products control Common and German Wasp populations

We have done extensive studies around New Zealand with Beekeepers to show that bees have no attraction to the Hawkeye Wasp Bait or Wasp Lure. üêù

#wasps #CommonWasp #GermanWasp #Waspnests #Pestcontrol

A Happy Median...

Most people just class all wasps as the same! Just an annoying animal with a bad temper! That couldn‚Äôt be further from the truth! They are wonderful animals that deserve some love!
üñ§üíõüñ§üíõ

They love my windfall pears! They cant resist them! And I can‚Äôt resist spending time with them. Places such as this where many species come together provides great opportunities to compare and study. Common wasps, German wasps, Median wasps, Hornets etc... are all here! No rule of six for these girls! They are all at the pub getting rather pissed on pear cider!
üçª

The larger wasp featured here is a Median wasp. The size difference is apparent when side by side to Common and German wasps. It was a Median wasp that stung me last year when I was hedge cutting. They often hang their football-size nests in bushes. Their sting packs a decent punch! 
üíâ

In life, you get the angry, bad tempered drunks! Some of the Common British ones are the worst! But don‚Äôt let them give others a bad name!
Our wasps along with our bees are incredible pollinators!!
üå∏

Remember.... there‚Äôd be a lot less fruit and beer in our glasses if it weren‚Äôt for those insects with the stripy arses!!

We found a fairly large underground wasp nest.
If you come across one of these be careful not to get too close or to disturb the nest.
The wasps can become very aggressive and attack you in large numbers. If that happens run for a bit and then drop to the ground. There is a good chance the swarm that followed you will just fly over you and miss you. Don‚Äôt forget the dropping to the ground though. They are fast and you can‚Äôt outrun them.

Some Red Admiral butterflies, Median wasps and German wasps all feeding on fermenting sap oozing from an oak trunk. 

The 2nd photo shows a queen Median wasp, which very closely resemble hornets (the only social wasp in the U.K. larger than the median wasp) and the 3rd-5th photos show a worker Median chasing a smaller German wasp. 
Median wasps can be distinguished from other wasps by the yellow ‚Äò7‚Äô shaped markings mirrored either side of the thorax. German wasps can be most easily distinguished by the 4 yellow spots sitting behind the thorax (vaguely form a black ‚Äò+‚Äô shape, see picture 5) being equally distanced. In common wasps, the bottom 2 yellow spots very nearly touch. They show the size of the Median wasps well here.
The Red Admirals were surprisingly confident - perhaps induced by the alcohol in the fermenting sap..? They would often hold their ground and even chase off the small German wasps, with frequent flicks of their wings to impose their presence (shown in the 1st video with the aggressive Median wasp worker). 
When their wings were closed, the red admirals were incredibly well camouflaged against the trunk bark (final video)

I was just thinking it's far to hot to be going out in the garden or to a nature reserve to get some new shots but I found this German Wasp collecting wood from my wicker decoration. I carefully snapped off the piece of wicker and surprisingly the wasp stayed put. I inserted the stick into a cookie box and grabbed a box of Kelloggs Krave to use as the backdrop. After the shoot, I put a plate of water down near where the cookie box was and waited for my subject to have a complimentary drink for its efforts before setting it free and away from chewing my wicker decoration any more than it had done.... Maori legend says that the King of the forest put the white tuft on the neck of the Tui so that he would forever be reminded of the great act of cowardice Tui committed.  I think that may have annoyed Tui and turned him into a major bully!  On Friday I was near the window when a small White-eye hit it so hard, he instantly broke his neck.  There was a Tui chasing him and as he dropped to the ground, the Tui followed him down and grabbed him with both claws and pecked the life out of him.  Tui then stopped to see if the White-eye was moving, flew to the nearby fence, checked again, looked at me, wiped his beak on the fence and flew off! Far out!!!!

Who are you? Identifying the #waspsinmygarden as I always got them confused. Experts among my readers, please let me know, if I'm wrong üôáüèª‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏èüôè
(1-3) #commonwasp aka #vespulavulgaris aka #gemeinewespe. The upside-down hammer black mark on her face is a hint. 
(4-6) #germanwasp aka #vespulagermanica aka #deutschewespe. The typical hint is the diamond/rhomb mark on the first ring and the three black dots on the face (the two small dots are hard to see on the screenshot of the video).
(7 & 8) #europeanpaperwasp aka #polistesdominula aka #gallischefeldwespe aka #hausfeldwespe is my favorite wasp. Their way to fly with the hanging legs and their orange antennae & legs make them easier to identify. Last year there were three of them in the #urbangarden, always on the drinking station for the bees. Now there are lots of them, big and small üíõüñ§üß°

Sorry, if I bored you with the #bronzefennel, but I'm simply amaze by it's visitors üòç Identified today:
(1 & 2) #deltaunguiculata aka #greatpotterwasp on the left and (probably) a #germanwasp aka #vespulagermanica on the right.
(3) A #gasteruptionjaculator on the left, a #greenbottlefly in the middle, a #europeanpaperwasp aka #polistesdominula and later an unidentified #bee on the left
(4) A #syrittapipiens aka a #thickleggedhoverfly.
(5) At the beginning, on the right: a #grasscarryingwasp aka #isodontiamexicana.

(1-5) If you remember, I posted about the black eggs on the #jerusalemartichoke on May, 20th. The first two must have hatched on Sunday morning. I went to the garden only in the evening (5). On Monday morning I saw the other ones just hatching (1-3). They were still pale. Later in the evening after I came home from work they turned dark, like the first ones I found on Sunday (4). They were already gone, when I looked for them today. I'm not sure, what they are. But probably #nymphs of either #damselbug or #assasinbug
(6) Probably a coincidence or possibly not, I found an adult one on the sweet grass I grow for my cats.
(7) A #bumblebee sleeping (?) on the #onionflower
(8) I think, there's a #germanwasp nest somewhere nearby, because I've seen it a few times in the garden. Not the kind of #wasp I like to have in the garden, to be honest üôà
(9) I saw a #lesserstagbeetle crawling slowly yesterday evening.
(10) A tiny #bug on the  #silvertansy

Four of the pollinators netted today in Manse garden as part of my #30dayswildchallenge.

Cryptic Bumblebee, Bombus cryptarum, queen. White-tailed cryptic complex includes three species. I have based ID on collar shape. 
Tree Bumblebee, Bombus hypnorum. A species that only arrived in the south of the UK at the start of the century, it has moved north quickly and found over most of the UK.

German Wasp, Vespula germanica, queen. Although its name is quite geographic specific this species is now commonly found in almost all continents.

Tree Wasp, Dolichovespula sylvestris, worker. Though called the Tree Wasp their nests will also be found hanging from houses and underground.

A European wasp queen chewing on the veranda chair.

It is quite common for many species of wasps to chew on wood. Referred to as ‚Äúgirdling‚Äù, this is one of the more common ways they gather raw material used to make nests. As you know, wood is used to make paper and is referred to as cellulose. It just so happens that cellulose makes great wasps nests and many species including the common paper, European hornet, yellow jackets and potter wasps all girdle wood for their nests.

Mahlzeit! - Summertime in #austriaüá¶üáπ is amazing. Enjoying a BBQ in the garden and perhaps some nice deserts and fruits and Ice Cream. You however need to be fast eating these sweet delights as you soon will be circled by those #yellow #hunters. The #germanwasp (Vespula germanica) is widely distributed in native Europe but have successfully expanded to North and South America, North Africa, parts of Asia and Australia. They are vital to our ecosystem as they keep #insect numbers down as their prey consists of Flies, Caterpillars and multiple other insects. But they are also known to eat carrion, fruit, honeydew, processed human food and garbage. Workers are known to be opportunistic #predators and #scavengers They are efficient at #hunting for small, live food sources and at collecting from large stationary sources. This is also why they have been so successful spreading throughout globally. In my picture you can see a worker #wasp after a successful Fly hunt. I stood there and observed the whole process as she took her prey apart until only this little protein ball was left she took back to her nest to feed their larvae. These insects are, like bees, social and have a queen, whose main purpose is to lay eggs, multiple workers and drones (male wasps) however wasp colonies are smaller and they defend their nest more aggressively then bees do. #socialinsects #yellowjacket #insects #insectphotography #nikond500 #nikon #wildplanet #wildlifephotography #wildlifepassion #wildaustria #nationalparkkalkalpen #bugs #insectguru #ip_insects #nature #entomology #animallover #animalbehavior #animals #macrophotography #discover

There isn't just one species of social was in the UK but several. Some can be quite hard to distinguish between without close examination. I netted this queen in my wee office and popped it in a pot in fridge to make docile. Once out of fridge I took quite a few photos from different angles so I could check online to ID. I have never tried to ID a social wasp to species level before.
I have decided this is a German Wasp, Vespula germanica, even though it doesn't possess the three black facial dots that normally confirm a wasp as this species. Although there are only two dots I confirmed that several other ID features are present and one website I consulted highlighted that though most reference media state the three dots¬†as being diagnostic to¬†Vespula germanica they are not always present. Might try IDing wasps again as it was quite fun!
